title: For Sale/Trade:  1943 Mauser Kar 98 8mm Bolt Action Rifle
postcontent:
I have a Mauser 98 with the code "bcd" marked on the receiver. I believe this means that at least the receiver was made in "Gustloff Werke, Werk Wiemar, Weimar". The reason why I say that is because some of serial numbers on the bolt do not match, like so many other Mauser's in circulation. However, the entire rifle works flawlessly and the only missing piece would be a front sight hood. Since it has been in my possession, I have cleaned off all the grease and have shot up to about 40 rounds of 8mm. It is nice shooter and a great piece of history...if you don't mind the swastikas. This particular rifle has two swastikas, one on the receiver and one on the side of the barrel. There is also an "x" marked next to one of the swastikas which I think means this was Russian capture. Another spooky discovery I made with this rifle was a spot of dried blood on the inside of the handguard. Of course it could be some clumsy gunsmith's blood who cut himself or it could be from conflict. There is no real way to tell, but it certainly adds character to this rifle.

With the rifle I will also include several stripper clips that each hold five 8mm rounds. These insert at the top of the magazine like normal and also pop off when you close the bolt...if you can do it right.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WTS/WTT Century AK-74 + extras
postcontent:
I'm nervous with 5.45. 
Long story short, it makes me nervous. So I am going either 5.56x45 or 7.62x39. To that end, I'm selling this rifle.

It is a Century Arms 'M74', their AK-74. For those who don't know, the barrel isn't chrome lined. Otherwise it is a straight shooter, I've confirmed that the gun does not keyhole, and the 'bullet-muzzle' test has shown about 1/8" between the case and the muzzle, so the bore is definitely 5.45mm. I cannot speak to accuracy as this was the first gun I ever shot and still had trouble with the irons on my last outing to the range.

The condition is good. This rifle came from Century with great parkerizing, and except for the areas in front of the HG retainer and the sling loop it's still pretty good. (see pics). The wood is a little off, I tried refinishing the handguards, which came-out so-so, and the Buttstock still had original Bulgarian shellac. I can strip and re-shellac the buttstock if desired. I can include the original ugbug plastic Century put on it, but for some reason the original upper HG is loose (wood and polyamide still tight)

The bore is in great shape, I've been meticulous (read: anal retentive) about keeping it clean after shooting. The bore is shiny with clear rifling and no pitting. Have shot about 200 rounds through it.

Some accessories were bought for the rifle. Polish sling, mag pouch, bipod, and steel magazine. Including a K-var 5.56/5.45 buttstock cleaning kit and half a bag of bore patches. Also included is 270+ rounds of 7N6 ammunition and the original 4 C10/C21 magazines.

Fore-notice, any potential exchange will include presentation of ID and signature of a bill of sale/receipt.
